{{EngvarB|date=October 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}} {{Malay name|Sairol|Sahari}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Sairol Sahari | fullname = Sairol bin Haji Sahari | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1983|04|09}} | birth_place = [[Brunei]] | height = {{height|m=1.74}} | currentclub = [[Kasuka FC]] | clubnumber = 16 | position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]] | years1 = 2002–2004 | clubs1 = [[Brunei (Malaysia Premier League team)|Brunei FA]]| caps1= | goals1= | years2 = 2004–2006 | clubs2 = NBT FC | caps2= | goals2= | years3 = 2006–2016 | clubs3 = [[Brunei DPMM FC|DPMM]]| caps3= | goals3= | years4 = 2010–2011 | clubs4 = → [[Indera SC]] (loan)| caps4= | goals4= | years5 = 2017– | clubs5 = [[Kasuka FC]] | caps5= | goals5=2 | nationalyears1 = 2001 | nationalyears2 = 2002–2005 | nationalyears3 = 2003–2014 | nationalcaps1=1 | nationalgoals1 =0 | nationalcaps2 = | nationalgoals2 = | nationalcaps3= 9| nationalgoals3= 0 | nationalteam1=[[Brunei national under-23 football team|Brunei U23]] | nationalteam2 = [[Brunei national under-21 football team|Brunei U21]] | nationalteam3=[[Brunei national football team|Brunei]] | pcupdate = 26 November 2018 | ntupdate = 22 January 2018 }}
'''Sairol Sahari''' is a [[Brunei]]an [[association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Kasuka FC]] of the [[Brunei Super League]] as a [[defender (association football)|defender]].
Sairol began his career as a young left-sided midfielder for the [[Brunei M-League Team|Brunei team]] which played in the Malaysian league system.<ref>{{cite web |title=Malaysia 2003|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/malay03.html|date=17 February 2005|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> After leaving the country's representative side in 2004, he helped NBT FC gain promotion to the [[Brunei Premier League|domestic top flight]]. He moved to [[DPMM FC]] in 2006 when the club had entered the [[Malaysia Premier League]] in Brunei FA's place. He was sent on loan to [[Indera SC]] in 2010 while DPMM was prevented from playing in the [[S.League]] due to a [[Brunei national football team#Suspension|FIFA suspension of Brunei]].<ref>{{cite web |title=BPL under watchful eyes of DPMM FC|url=http://www.bt.com.bn/sports-national/2011/03/03/bpl-under-watchful-eyes-dpmm-fc|date=3 March 2011|publisher=The Brunei Times|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>
On 25 April 2016, Sairol suffered an [[anterior cruciate ligament injury]] in training and was absent for the remaining [[2016 S.League]] season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sairol out for the season|url=http://www.bt.com.bn/sports-national/2016/04/28/sairol-out-season|date=28 April 2016|publisher=The Brunei Times|accessdate=28 April 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502011805/http://www.bt.com.bn/sports-national/2016/04/28/sairol-out-season|archivedate=2 May 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
Sairol has since joined [[Kasuka FC]] as assistant coach for the [[2017 Brunei Super League]], with a view to returning to action in the next year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sairol aiming to bounce back next year |url=http://www.brusports.com/2017/04/12/sairol-aiming-to-bounce-back-next-year/|date=12 April 2017|publisher=BruSports News|accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> He registered as a player for Kasuka for the [[2018-19 Brunei Super League|2018-19 season]] and has impressed since, scoring against [[Najip-Bakes FC|Najip-Bakes]] and [[Indera SC]].<ref>{{cite web |title=SAIROL RETURNS STRONGER AFTER ACL INJURY|url=https://www.brusports.com/2018/11/17/sairol-returns-stronger-after-acl-injury/|date=17 November 2018|publisher=BruSports News|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref>
==International career== Still 18 years of age, Sairol was chosen to represent [[Brunei national under-23 football team|Brunei]] at the [[2001 Southeast Asian Games|2001 SEA Games]] held in [[Kuala Lumpur]], and made his sole appearance against [[Malaysia national under-23 football team|the hosts]] and only lasting about half-an-hour.<ref>{{cite web |title=South East Asian Games 2001 (Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia) - Match Details|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/sea01-det.html|date=20 September 2001|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref> Sairol then played for the [[Brunei national under-21 football team|under-21s]] at the [[2002 Hassanal Bolkiah Trophy|2002]] and [[2005 Hassanal Bolkiah Trophy]].<ref>{{cite web |title=ASEAN U-21 Championship 2005 (Piala Hassanal Bolkiah)|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/asean-u21-05.html|date=17 February 2005|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>
Sairol made his international debut for the [[Brunei national football team|Wasps]] in 2008 (he was an unused substitute in the [[2004 AFC Asian Cup qualification|2004 Asian Cup qualifying]] matches), when his club side DPMM was sent as the nation's representatives at the [[2008 AFF Suzuki Cup qualification]] held in [[Cambodia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=DPMM FC head to Cambodia|url=http://www.bt.com.bn/local_sport/2008/10/15/dpmm_fc_head_to_cambodia|date=15 October 2008|publisher=The Brunei Times|accessdate=30 March 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402173841/http://www.bt.com.bn/local_sport/2008/10/15/dpmm_fc_head_to_cambodia|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Brunei failed to qualify after one win and one draw. He was picked for the next two qualification rounds in [[2012 AFF Suzuki Cup qualification|2012]] and [[2014 AFF Suzuki Cup qualification|2014]].<ref>{{cite web |title=DPMM Reinforcements For Brunei|url=http://www.aseanfootball.org/v2/?p=9717|date=17 September 2012|publisher=ASEAN Football Federation|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=AFF SUZUKI CUP QUALIFIERS: Reserve power propels Myanmar past Brunei|url=http://www.aseanfootball.org/v2/?p=18015|date=16 October 2014|publisher=ASEAN Football Federation|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>
